         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Old Botanic Garden, ¶ Adelaide,  ¶ South Australia ¶ May 26th, 1855. ¶ Sir,...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">M55.05.26</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Francis to William Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Directors' Correspondence, vol. 74, letter number 69.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For a published version of this letter, see Best (1986), pp. 163-4.</p>
               </note>Old Botanic Garden,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Adelaide, </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">South Australia</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">May 26th, 1855.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Annotated in pencil in an unrecognised hand:</seg> not answered.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Sir,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Some twenty years ago I was honored with several letters from you relative to British Botany, and also some contributions of Mosses from your son. If you remember my name at all it will be only that I was at that time publishing my Analysis of British Ferns,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Francis (1837).</p>
               </note> which you kindly permitted me to dedicate to yourself, an honor I was justly proud of — My Grammar of Botany and Little English Flora<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Respectively Francis (1840) and Francis (1839).</p>
               </note> succeeded During the many years that succeeded I have passed a life full of vicissitudes, through all of which I have retained a love of Botany, though greatly curbed by absorbing occupations—often ill health, family misfortunes, and the care of a large family. Now I am resident at this City of the Antipodes, endeavouring to establish a nursery amid the disadvantages of a 2 years drought (during all of which time the earth has never been wet a foot deep) and famine prices of provisions (10d for 2 lbs of bread and lately 5d for a lb of potatoes)—occasionally amusing myself with a ramble over hills and s<seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">cru</hi>
               </seg>b botanizing — But the flowers remain many of them strangers and small, stiff and sombre strangers they must remain, for we have no book on our general Flora, except the very imperfect one of the Prodromus of Brown,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>R. Brown (1810).</p>
               </note> at least I know of none other.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Now, Sir, the object of my troubling you, is to suggest that you yourself, if possible, if not your son or Mr Gray, would assist the colonists here and elsewhere in our botanical pursuits, by preparing a work in English upon the plan of your valuable British Flora —(Phanerogamia).<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>W. Hooker (1830), or subsequent editions.</p>
               </note> It might be confined to the Australian Colonies. To be called the Australia Flora—published at £1.11.6 — or it might be extended to all the Colonies, and called The Botany of the British Colonies, Vol 1, Australia, <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Vol 2 Canada, Vol 3 India, Vol 4 Cape of G. Hope—&amp; others if necessary. Such a series would be most valuable, and as far as our colonies are concerned it would pay well. Sir W. Denison, Governor General at Sydney, is a great patron of the Natural Sciences—My little experience of localities &amp;c. is quite at your service, and one of our best Botanists, Dr Müller, lately Colonial Botanist at Victoria, is enthusiastic, kind and gentlemanly, &amp; from my long acquaintance with him I am sure he would be proud to assist, &amp; I to forward any letter to him, though as he is about to move I cannot give his address.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>M joined the North Australian Exploring Expedition in July 1855; see A. Gregory to M, 26 May 1855 (in this edition as 55-05-26a). </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I date this from The Old Botanic Garden, here, as my place is called, because it was once laid out for that purpose, but soon abandoned as such—I hope and believe that we shall soon have established here a really good botanic Garden in a well chosen beautiful spot—but having now a sort of interregnum between the departure of one Governor and the arrival of another, I am in some doubts how he may view the expenditure, necessary at a time when the Colonial revenue is decreasing—although £3000 for the 1st yrs expenditure has been voted and a governmental committee appointed—If it goes on I hope and trust to be appointed the Superintendent and for which I have a great claim, for it will have been entirely from my urging the government here for these 5 years-past, and from my furnishing all their plans and estimates, that it will have been commenced at all—It may hereafter perhaps be my duty to write to you upon this matter &amp; beg contributions—</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">I have the honor to be Sir</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your Obedient Servant,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Francis.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Sir Wm J Hooker</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>&amp;c &amp;c &amp;c</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">P.S. Some British plants are certainly natives here, as <name key="Poa%20annua">Poa annua</name>-<name key="Polygonum%20aviculare">Polygonum aviculare</name> — <name key="Sonchus%20oleraceus">Sonchus oleraceus</name> — <name key="Herniaria%20glabra">Herniaria glabra</name>, <name key="Malva%20sylvestris">Malva sylvestris</name>, and 2 or 3 <name key="Chenopodium">Chenopodium</name>s — others now common but introduced, as <name key="Eschscholtzia%20californica">Eschscholtzia californica</name>, <name key="Medicago%20lupulina">Medicago lupulina</name> — <name key="Melilotus%20leucantha">Melilotus leucantha</name> — <name key="Calandrinia%20grandiflora">Calandrinia grandiflora</name> — <name key="Oxalis%20cernua">Oxalis cernua</name> — <name key="Papaver%20rhoeas">Papaver rhoeas</name> — And our native Flora, are almost all graminaceae, compositae, or papilionacea. <name key="Chara%20hispida">Chara hispida</name> is common in our abominable River Torrens—and also a Vallisneria — all other rivers besides that and the Murray are dry 6 months in the year.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="">The paper has been folded, and the resultant exposed part of p. 4 addressed:</seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Sir William J. Hooker &amp;c &amp;c &amp;c</seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Kew Gardens—</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>England</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>and inscribed by Francis 'Paid'. It has been postmarked 'Paid Adelaide S.A. MY29 1855', 'Australian Packet, Liverpool SP […] [C.O. 55[K]', and 'Paid, CR 21SP21, 1855'.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
